We recommended to the management to:
Submit immediately the relevant lacking documents on foreign travel expenses incurred to facilitate our further audit action. Secure documents from LMP-Bukidnon Chapter and VMLP-Bukidnon Chapter regarding the breakdown of paid registration fees to accurately account the same, including the pertinent documents necessary for the proper liquidation thereof. Non-submission by management may warrant issuance of audit suspension or disallowance, as the case may be;
Stop the practice of drawing check in favor to the league/association rather than to the concerned personnel to establish accountability over such disbursed amount to be treated as cash advance, subject to proper documentation and liquidation;
Ensure that expenses related to foreign travel be recorded to Travelling Expenses – Foreign account; and,
Strictly observe prudence and judiciousness in the utilization of public funds.

We recommended to the management the following courses of action:

1. To rectify the various deficiencies observed in this memorandum, we demand for the immediate submission to the Office of the Auditor of the deed of transfer like Deed of Donation and other necessary supporting documents related to the previously constructed infrastructure project at Barangay Kiharong in order to legalize the conveyance of the ownership of the property to the recipient barangay; 

    Further, we recommended to the Municipal Accountant to:

2. Furnish the Office of the Auditor of copy of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) showing that the previously constructed infrastructure project at Barangay Kiharong is aptly accounted and properly recorded in the book of accounts of the barangay;

3. Submit to the Office of the Auditor the copies of Certificate of Project Turn-over and Acceptance and Inspection Report both signed and attested by the Punong Barangay to confirm that the rehabilitation project at Barangay Dologon was fully implemented and 100% complete; and

Capitalize major improvement/repair of a particular asset especially if it improves the quality of the asset, extends the estimated useful life and reduces the associated operating costs.

We recommended to the Management the following courses of action:

To request the Sanggunian Bayan to enact an SB Resolution allowing reimbursement of communication expenses declaring there-in the office, designation, and allowable rates;

To submit the lacking Statements of Account or billing statements and Official Receipts, invoice or machine validated payments to the Office of the Auditor for review and validation;

To refrain from subscribing to cellular phones applications such as Netflix, Playstore, etcetera so as not to incur additional charges that are prohibited by law; and

4. Henceforth, to ensure that all payments for communication expenses are duly supported with complete and proper supporting documents.

We recommended to the Management to:

 Instruct the following officers to submit documents in order for the team to conduct further audit procedures to determine the validity and propriety of the transactions:

The Municipal Budget Officer to submit documents which may support the existence of available appropriation or any ordinance supporting the maintenance of a savings account for the heavy equipment loan and seed money for the regular livelihood loan of the LGU;
The Municipal Accountant to submit the following:
Breakdown of all the cash inflows of its DBP savings account to which the disbursement for the SLL payment was withdrawn;
Subsidiary ledgers or accounting records to support that the loan proceeds from the LGU’s regular loan is sufficient to cover the disbursement for the SLL; 
The Municipal Treasurer to submit a certification that there is actually fund available in the DBP savings account since the check originally issued was from the account LBP 2102-0000-24 of GF Proper and also submit a certified copy of SB Resolution on the purpose of opening the DBP – savings bank account.

Discontinue the practice of giving out loan which has no complete legal basis; and

Discontinue paying for the outstanding loan balances of its employees to financial institutions.

We recommended that the management implement the required inventory process under the Manual on New Government Accounting System and the Rules and Regulations on Supply and Property Management in the Local Governments, specifically by doing the following:

The requisitioning unit, upon withdrawal of the supplies and materials for project implementation, prepare the Requisition and Issue Slip so that withdrawal, issuance and transfer of accountability may properly take place;
The GSO maintain the required stock cards for each supplies and materials to keep a complete and updated record of the supplies and materials;
The GSO prepare and submit, monthly, the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (together with the RIS) as basis of the Accounting Office in recording its utilization in the proper expense or asset account; and
The Municipality provide proper warehouse and storage on the supplies and materials and designate warehouse keeper who shall be in-charge in the safekeeping and issuances of supplies and materials.

We recommended the following:

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

Create a committee to undertake the reconciliation of under/over remittance of premiums/contributions and loan amortizations and to coordinate with GSIS, Pag-ibig, Philhealth and Financial Institutions to be able to reconcile such records;

After determination of the under and over remittance, the municipality shall pay to the employees the excess deductions from the payroll and the employee/s shall refund the amount remitted to financial institutions without corresponding payroll deduction and submit copy of payroll/receipts thereof;

Record in the SL of the employee the loan amount availed by the employee; 

Stop the practice of paying the due amount of employee’s loan without the corresponding salary deduction; and

Make the necessary internal controls in the Municipal Accountant’s Office that would warrant the meticulous monitoring of the mandatory and loan deductions of each employee and their subsequent remittances to prevent over and under remittances of above mandatory accounts.

